Bacon considered that it is of greatest importance to science not to keep doing intellectual discussions or seeking merely contemplative aims, but that it should work for the bettering of mankind's life by bringing forth new inventions, having even stated that "inventions are also, as it were, new creations and imitations of divine works".[35][pageÂ needed] He explored the far-reaching and world-changing character of inventions, such as the printing press, gunpowder and the compass.
